uthor": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Protecting Pacific Island Children & Women during Economic and Food Crises", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-pacific-island-children-women-during-economic-and-food-crises", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e21d5cf2f82b99c0c98735dd1f5da37cecc3c6e35efa6542269d75091ba9a539"}, "2": {"node_id": "6507da09-856c-4252-9514-fa0ea1918285", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-pacific-island-children-women-during-economic-and-food-crises", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "08cdd89a6f0daf7d22ea616d2d3a5edb31c00a2aba721d1174bc5a2c0441be34"}}, "hash": "f43a5045b6c1ed31b2f8c360adfd1a1967db278b4ab424500936fd51e93b19df", "text": "The second point to make is that the resources needed for scaling up interventions for children are moderate. Providing micronutrients for the world\u2019s children who lack essential vitamins and minerals would cost just $60 million per year, and yield annual benefits of more than $1 billion185\u2014 implying a 1,500% rate of return.186 The World Bank also reports that interventions to improve child nutrition outcomes could result in productivity gains reaching up to 10% of lifetime earnings re-gained for the individual, and for some countries, up to 2-3% of long-run GDP growth re-claimed.187 Studies have demonstrated very positive associations between schooling and productivity, and height and productivity, suggesting that investment in children\u2019s nutrition brings both private and public returns on investment.188,189 An additional $1-1.5 billion yearly spending on immunization could save 1 million young lives annually in the 72 poorest countries.190 The total additional yearly bill for bringing quality basic education to all the world\u2019s children is estimated by UNICEF, the World Bank and UNESCO to be between $9 billion and $15 billion.191 In other words, we could not only save a young child from death, but we could also help him or her complete basic education by the age of 13 by investing altogether no more than $2,200 per child.192 A broad review of the empirical evidence by Psacharopoulos and Patrinos (2004) suggests that the estimated rate of return to one additional year of schooling is about 10% on average\u2014and this figure increases when one focuses on poorer countries such as those in Africa.193 This calculation considers earnings which accrue to the individual, and does not yet consider the social benefits of a 185 Copenhagen Consensus (2008) http://www.copenhagenconsensus.com/Default.aspx?ID=953. See Report: Horton, S., Begin, F.,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "398c6a54-57cd-40af-bcf6-9aac6692216c": {"__data__": {"id_": "398c6a54-57cd-40af-bcf6-9aac6692216c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-pacific-island-children-women-during-economic-and-food-crises", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Protecting Pacific Island Children & Women during Economic and Food Crises", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/protecting-pacific-island-children-women-during-economic-and-food-crises", "Author"