al drugs in health facilities Rationale: pharmaceutical supply is a capital intensive element of the system that may be greatly sensitive to economic downturn; consumption in public facilities providing free access is expected to increase during economic crises; if charged consumption will decrease Numerator: number of drugs among 20 selected available Denominator: 20 Interpretation: decreased availability may indicate reductions in budgets from Governments or difficulties in the supply system due to transport costs or similar reasons Pharmaceutical out of pocket expenditure Household pulse survey Quarterly NGO Indicator definition: Expenditure incurred on drugs and medical supplies Rationale: It is expected that access to drugs from private providers will decrease but drug consumption from public facilities with free access may increase due to increased self-care Analysis: quantification of closed responses and qualitative analysis of open responses Interpretation: increased out of pocket expenditure may indicate economic struggle and may push households into poverty Protecting Pacific Island children and women during economic and food crises: Working Edition One for advocacy, debate and guidance 76 AREAS TO MONITOR AND INDICATORS SOURCE FREQUENCY RESPONSIBLE REMARKS Availability and price of 20 essential drugs Pharmacy/medicine outlet questionnaire Quarterly NGO Indicator definition: Availability and price of drugs in private pharmacies/medicines retailers Rationale: Price of medicines and medical supplies is very sensitive to economic downturn Numerator: Price of selected medicines during the period of study Denominator: Baseline prices of selected medicines Interpretation: Increase in price reduces access DTP 3 coverage Health facility questionnaire (health facility records) Quarterly MOH Indicator definition: Number of children having received the 3rd dose of DTP Rationale: Indicator measures the access of children to health services and the adherence to preven