ultural Organisation UNFPA - United Nations Populations Fund UNICEF - United Nations Children Fund WB - World Bank WMO - World Meteorological Organisation List of Acronyms 4. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries Day 1 set a foundation for the following days by looking at how national priorities and the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) can be integrated into national and sectoral planning and budget frameworks. Session 1 - Objective: To better understand poverty and MDG trends in the context of national development efforts in Western Pacific MDGs monitoring and reporting in Western Pacific, Carol Flore- Smereczniak, UNDP Pacific Centre The presentation provided some basic information about the MDGs, such as the source of the MDGs and the contextual background of the Millennium Declaration. Emphasis was put on the inter-relatedness of the MDGs, the revised MDG Framework since September 2007, the minimum threshold that the MDGs provide for every one, the centrality of gender to achieve all the goals, and the synergies between the MDGs and human rights instruments such as CRC, CEDAW and others. The role of UNDP as scorekeeper and campaign manager of the MDGs, and the fact that the MDGs represent selected country priorities and needs was looked at, before considering the reporting and progress of the five countries on each Millennium Development Goal. Generally, countries have made some progress on some goals, but these are insufficient to achieve all MDGs by 2015. The importance of linking national priorities requiring additional attention to national and sectoral plans so that budget allocations can be made for implementation was addressed, along with monitoring and evaluation. The role of CSOs in the MDG framework and the need to talk about the MDGs along with the Millennium Declaration were stressed. MDG 1: Definition and trends of poverty in Western Pacific, and policy implications, David Abbott, UNDP Pacific Centre The presentation on definition and trends of poverty highlighted the fact that all data provided came from Household Income and Expenditure Surveys (HIES), as all countries in the region have either had a HIES in the past 4 years, or will do so in the next year or two. Most countries will also have new census rounds in the next two years. Together, these will provide a significant increase in the source of information for the MDGs and other aspects of evidence-based policy-making. Poverty has many characteristics, comprising both low incomes and poverty of opportunity or lack of access to services. Women are often more severely affected by poverty and face more constraints than men to move out of poverty. A suggested Pacific definition of poverty is hardship which reflects an inadequate level of sustainable human development. Poverty and hardship can be measured both quantitatively through poverty lines and qualitatively through participatory assessments. The importance of understanding poverty and undertaking a gender sensitive poverty analysis to inform the formulation of gender responsive pro-poor policy making and appropriate budget decisions was highlighted. Indicators of poverty and inequality, and measures to break the self-perpetuating cycle of poverty were also discussed. The plenary discussions on MDGs and poverty highlighted the need for assistance to Nauru to update their data so that a National MDG Report can be compiled. Vanuatu indicated that their national data is not always disaggregated by sex and does not always reflect the reality as some areas (women, the disabled,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6db6e805-f580-474e-b26a-691d8c169fea": {"__data__": {"id_": "6db6e805-f580-474e-b26a-691d8c169fea", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f7484282b82b0bf31b0c97ccd2e31e58765b8bc74c10229d40016c6b68623162"}}, "hash": "f7484282b82b0bf31b0c97ccd2e31e58765b8bc74c10229d40016c6b68623162", "text": "etc) are not targeted. It was also 5. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries stressed that the US$1 a day indicator is not relevant for PICs. Countries pointed out that they were still working on the poverty data, which should not be released until the data has been endorsed. Fiji pointed out the difficulty to undertake monitoring and evaluation of the Strategic Development Plan as there are problems with data, adding that resources would be required to support ministries and departments to update the data. Solomon Islands questioned why many countries have not made sufficient progress on the MDGs and what needed to be done. The need to maintain focus on reporting as an initial step and to address issues highlighted in the reporting through national / sectoral plans and appropriate budget envelopes was emphasised. Participants also queried whether loneliness can be looked at as part of poverty in the Pacific context, and how this would be researched. It was explained that the gradual breakdown of the traditional caring society and the impact of monetisation with children leaving the islands as they reach a certain age was having an effect, including resulting in loneliness. It was suggested that the number of households headed by elderly people could be examined to see whether they are better or worse off. Session 2 - Objective: Practical steps to integrate the MDGs into planning and budget frameworks, taking into account other frameworks such as the Mauritius Strategy and the Pacific Plan, chaired by Siliga Kofe, UNESCAP Integrating the MDGs into National Sustainable Development Strategies, including Monitoring and Evaluation, Matthias Bruckner, UNDESA A National Sustainable Development Strategy is a coordinated, participatory and iterative process (rather than a product) that supports national development. Deriving from the commitment of countries to prepare and implement NSDS in Rio in 1992 and reaffirmed in Johannesburg in 2002, NSDS are country driven and integrate economic, social and environmental pillars, and coordinate national strategies and sectoral plans. NSDS build upon existing information and processes to avoid duplication, and consider intra- and inter-generational equity for future generations. It is driven by broad participation of all stakeholders and partnership to foster ownership. There are different ways to organise an NSDS, depending on countries\u2019 institutional structures. A by-product of NSDS is that the process develops capacity for implementation. It focuses on priorities and outcomes for implementation and therefore has strong linkages to public investment and the budget. NSDS usually show strong coherence between international and national goals and targets. The MDGs are part of the sustainable development agenda, but sustainable development goes beyond the MDGs. Monitoring of NSDS is done at several levels: monitor the activities in the NSDS, monitor the effect and impact of NSDS on sustainable development, and monitor progress towards sustainable development (common indicators for the last two). Formulation of targets is important, and can be done in line with the MDGs, and with the involvement of National Statistical Offices throughout the process. From national strategy to sector plans: Why a longer-term vision must be translated into strategic objectives and sector plans to achieve the MDGs, David Smith, UNESCAP Pacific Island Countries have National Development Plans or National Sustainable Development Strategies (document). The issue is to what extent these plans reflect the principles of NSDS, which is the process surrounding the preparation of the plan. 6. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries Often, sustainable development principles are integrated in policies and programs, but problems are encountered during implementation due to the involvement of several departments, and a lack of focus on development objectives. Grounded in lengthy consultative process to establish a vision, NDPs/NSDS address economic and social progress, followed by a review to determine main development challenges. This results in a set of priorities to be addressed in national strategies or visions, lead to sector plans, link to budget allocation and donor funds, and translate into development outcomes reflecting positive changes in people\u2019s lives. However, often linkages do not work because they do not exist, or there is a lack of monitoring and evaluation, or poor coordination between ministries and central agencies, or financial management reforms are underway. Examples of countries\u2019 institutional set- ups were provided for Vanuatu, Nauru, Tuvalu, Fiji and Solomon Islands, indicating differences in the way plans are developed and implemented. Countries face similar problems (slow implementation), and most deal with process (implementation, getting the budget in line with the priorities, etc.) rather than the document itself. The way forward is to link national plans to strategic activities of the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d3153b6d-7a08-491b-a9f3-5a404e81cdfe": {"__data__": {"id_": "d3153b6d-7a08-491b-a9f3-5a404e81cdfe", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6f703dce98502e30a4c6b74571fec8dc40c06837db2e72b5893df1c46cf8cd60"}, "3": {"node_id": "50185b7a-9b0c-45c9-ad90-bef895fac6bd", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2fcd89791b4a34ce1751c4fdbd0a8cb997a756b5e3a21647f08dfb9410a5a8e6"}}, "hash": "eb22be719af613093a57c75df05e32e8d73ab82ebd5ba55b1bd5cfeeba1381e6", "text": "plan and develop indicators for monitoring by government and non-government actors. Linkages between the MDGs, the Mauritius Strategy and the Pacific Plan: Implications for NSDS implementation, including monitoring of progress, Philippe Boull\u00e9, Consultant The presentation highlighted the added value of the Mauritius Strategy amidst a multiplicity of other frameworks, and how it can be integrated into national development plans along with the MDGs and the Pacific Plan. The Preamble of the Mauritius Strategy states that as a follow-up to the Barbados Programme of Action (1994), the Strategy recognises the special circumstances and vulnerabilities of SIDS in achieving sustainable development, and is therefore one of the most important UN frameworks for SIDS. The Mauritius Strategy reaffirms the international status of 49 SIDS Member States as a specific group of countries at the UN and at international level. It is a partnership agreement containing obligations for both the international community and small islands states. Embedded in sustainable development, the Mauritius Strategy (proposals for development) can be summarised around four clusters: natural resources; economic issues; social issues; and governance and political issues. The MDGs, the Mauritius Strategy (MS) and the Pacific Plan represent a hierarchy of complementary frameworks which countries need to address within their NSDS or other national planning instruments. While the MDGs are a global framework for all countries, the Mauritius Strategy is an agenda specifically for SIDS, and the Pacific Plan provides a regional framework for Pacific Islands Countries (PICs). While there are systems in place to report on the MDGs and the Pacific Plan, countries need to develop their own monitoring and reporting of the MS which was adopted only in 2005, using existing tools, institutions and people, and involving all stakeholders. Countries have already done much to implement the MS, but this is not being captured in countries\u2019 reporting. Implementation of the MS requires its integration with national budgets, which can be done through linkages made in the NSDS. The plenary discussions revealed that participants were grappling with how to reconcile the MDGs, the Pacific Plan, the Mauritius Strategy and the NSDS. It was explained that the Pacific Plan is a guiding plan for the Pacific and provides a definition of sustainable development to which PICs may or may not have paid attention, while the Mauritius Strategy is a Strategy for SIDS. One way forward is to incorporate the framework of sustainable development as laid out in the PP within the NSDS or NDP, and use the MDGs as a guide to set measurable goals and monitor progress. The NSDS should address the MS at the same time, as there are 7. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries strong linkages among these various frameworks. CSOs have an important role to play when governments plan and implement programmes. While CSOs need to hold government accountable, governments need to include and educate CSOs on planning, implementation and the role of governments and CSOs respectively vis-\u00e0-vis the public. Group exercises addressed the following: Countries Do you have an NSDS? What is needed to strengthen existing planning process /NSDS? What support, if any, is required? Vanuatu Nauru Fiji Solomon Islands Priority Action and Agenda (10 years) National Sustainable Development Strategy (20 years) Sustainable Economic Empowerment Development Strategies 2008- 2010 No. Former NERRDP and MTDS both focused on recovery - Need to integrate an M & E framework - Revisit PAA to integrate missing sector - Consultations with ministries - Secure donor funding - Consultation process to involve wider communities - Systematic approach to address divisional /provincial /village levels - Mechanisms to align budget allocation to strategic outcomes deriving from the MDGs, MS, PP - Government to endorse planning framework or NSDS - Clarify role of non-state actors - Need to have clear enabling environment -Planning to be done around vertical / horizontal programmes - Integrate M & E into plans - Financial resources - Integration of MDGs into NSDS, support for M & E - Funding - Strategy development for smaller departments (women, culture, lands) - Costing tools - Capacity building - Institutional planning to put in place clear plans - Budgeting Tuvalu participants were absent on Day 1 8. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries The rationale for the workshop was costing and budgeting.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "50185b7a-9b0c-45c9-ad90-bef895fac6bd": {"__data__": {"id_": "50185b7a-9b0c-45c9-ad90-bef895fac6bd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6f703dce98502e30a4c6b74571fec8dc40c06837db2e72b5893df1c46cf8cd60"}, "2": {"node_id": "d3153b6d-7a08-491b-a9f3-5a404e81cdfe", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "eb22be719af613093a57c75df05e32e8d73ab82ebd5ba55b1bd5cfeeba1381e6"}}, "hash": "2fcd89791b4a34ce1751c4fdbd0a8cb997a756b5e3a21647f08dfb9410a5a8e6", "text": "Days 2 & 3 looked at how priorities to achieve the MDGs can be costed by introducing costing tools on education, health, HIV, and energy and how the tools can support policy development, including pro-poor, child-friendly and population policy. Session 3 - Objective: To look at the characteristics of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "575bf4f4-cf47-4073-8526-b3af211920c0": {"__data__": {"id_": "575bf4f4-cf47-4073-8526-b3af211920c0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d3a266743e9883a9071ddc15e1fbce2035314bfc6cdffc420a0d7c523fcf0ac0"}, "3": {"node_id": "38948dec-762b-4c31-948f-6d7e4e8275ee", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ec09c2f6549b22946aa0f2afdb6f596e9cf2c94db0e727f3d26cb11fa8ea5313"}}, "hash": "0de27fd61ee0af8e1e286bc14e2e579aa0b94ea9e6179c2827927d43c9787815", "text": "pro-poor and child-friendly policy, chaired by Simil Johnson, Vanuatu What constitutes pro-poor policy? Why are these important for achievement of the MDGs?, David Abbott, UNDP Pacific Centre Pro-poor policies aim to target those who are most disadvantaged, either in income or opportunities, in a way that will change their situation in relation to those who are more well-off. They aim to increase the income levels of those who are poor at a faster rate than for other groups, so that as income levels rise, there is an improvement in other MDG indicators and, subsequently, in the overall standard of human development. Anecdotal evidence suggests that generally there has been a decline in standards of living in PICs because policies have not been pro-poor. The characteristics of pro-poor policies include being labour rather than capital-intensive, targeting sectors where the poor are engaged, and generating income and employment for marginalised communities. A two-way causality between growth and MDGs suggest that the MDGs are both an end in themselves and a means to setting targets for achieving high quality, sustainable growth. Since the poor and disadvantaged are often concentrated in specific sectors, pro-poor policies would target resources to these sectors to reduce inequalities, including those between women and men. In linking national strategies, pro-poor policy and the budget, there is need to derive a long term vision which highlights pro-poor and sector priorities and strategies which are then translated into strategic outcomes to be achieved over a shorter time frame (3-5 years). These strategies and priorities are then costed and integrated into annual budgets and MTEF. Because economic growth is a necessary but insufficient condition for poverty reduction, it is important to address the redistributive aspects of economic growth, high population growth rates, access to basic services and resources, governance, and prioritising the budget. Child-friendly policies and child-friendly budgets: linkages with MDG achievement, Will Parks, UNICEF The presentation looked at how to place children at the centre of policies and budgets, and why. Child friendly policies are a subset of policy-making and are vital to governments who have ratified the CRC. The principles of universality, non-discrimination, indivisibility, participation and accountability seek to ensure that all policies reach all children without excluding anyone, and satisfy all of their needs. Policies should be holistic and take account of other sectors, and mobilise many actors in development for implementation, sustainability and give voice to the voiceless. In essence, conditions need to be developed so duty- bearers and right-holders have capacity to fulfil and exercise their respective rights. 9. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries Budgeting is a powerful tool to reduce poverty and analysis of the budget is a tool to keep children at the forefront of budget decisions. A child-friendly budget seeks to improve the condition of children, both girls and boys, in a country and focuses on education, health, protection, etc. Children experience poverty differently from adults and girls often experience poverty differently from boys. Consequently, poverty analysis should focus on children to determine whether they face lack (access to schooling, protection from abuse, nutrition, etc). Support is available from UN Agencies on costing tools, data analysis, and capacity strengthening in negotiation and harmonisation. Ecuador was mentioned as a strong advocacy model for child-friendly budget and child-friendly public policies. Session 3 - Objective: To look at the characteristics of population policy, chaired by David Abbott, UNDP Pacific Centre From Population and Development Policy to MDGs: The relationships between population and development variables, budgeting and MDG Progress in the Pacific, Jean Louis Rallu, UNFPA The presentation addressed the central role of population, including population projections, in MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting. The global context of the impact of population trends and structures (population momentum and window of opportunity) on development and MDG attainment was considered based on Pacific data. As the Pacific is late in reaching a window of opportunity, population projections in two hypotheses of rapid/slow fertility decline were presented for Solomon Islands, Fiji and Kiribati to illustrate possible trends in population size and dependency ratios and their benefits. Correlations calculated for a series of MDG indicators for 12 PICs illustrated the relationship between population growth, age structure and poverty/GDP per capita on one side, and MDG indicators levels and trends on the other.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "38948dec-762b-4c31-948f-6d7e4e8275ee": {"__data__": {"id_": "38948dec-762b-4c31-948f-6d7e4e8275ee", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development