fic-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c6e68df477c7f82784ba827b4495a13c45fd40ae54e720a9531595e11f6676f2"}, "3": {"node_id": "aba560a8-b013-4dbe-a13e-57895285a40f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f459dbba1b3128d7238f13f67d799f94be5f66bbd6424ce87038fbd36c88d962"}}, "hash": "e8de762f13d9a2c2981ba673cdac200a343912831894302a32bff0602bdae94b", "text": "growth affects the coverage of services, and noting also that there are significant correlations between total growth and poverty/ GDP per capita. Thus, the relationship between MDGs indicator levels and the likelihood of MDG attainment on one side and population/poverty variables on the other could be assessed for the Pacific, and awareness of participants on the role of population in development and state planning and budgeting was enhanced. There was much interest in the different types of policies. Participants discussed why countries should have population policies and what support they can receive to address these. It was explained that while people have the freedom to choose the number of children they can have, the family size determines how much and where resources are spent. Increasingly, people tend to have less children in order to have better quality of life. Nauru pointed out that there is no family planning and support is needed to address the growing population. Participants also recognize that people need to take more responsibility to improve their own lives and not always look for support elsewhere. Participants were keen to point out that the shift from an economic-centred approach to development to a people-centred approach focusing on women, children, the poor required a change in mindset and attitudes, as well as capacity building for both government and CSOs. Attention was drawn to the fact that there are many tools, approaches, filters which countries can use in their policy-making and planning (SWAPs, costing tools, peace and policy framework, etc). The aim of the workshop was to enhance participants\u2019 understanding of these various tools so they can choose the most appropriate ones, as \u201cplanning and policy making is deliciously messy\u201d. UN Agencies were asked to share guidelines on child-friendly policies and budgets. 10. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries Session 4 - Objective: To look at how policies in the health sector can be costed, chaired by Ethel Sigimanu, Solomon Islands MDG needs assessment and costing methodology, Yuba Raj Khatiwada, UNDP Regional Centre, Colombo This session built upon the presentations on pro-poor policy and from national strategy to sector plans respectively by looking at how MDG needs assessment (NA) and planning can address the challenges. Needs Assessment is a tool for MDG-based planning which answers the question: what (interventions, resources, strategies, capacity, etc) will it take to achieve the MDGs? NA strengthens coherence between planning and budget processes, provides a proper monitoring and accountability framework, and has a strictly bottom-up approach. NA is necessarily integrated with other frameworks such as the MTEF. The guiding principle is that some of the core MDGs are state responsibility. Therefore NA focuses on all interventions that require full or partial public financing in terms of both capital and operating expenses. The MDG NA methodology includes four steps: identify interventions critically needed to achieve MDGs by 2015; specify coverage target; estimate resources; and check results for synergy, consistency and robustness of the costing exercise. MDG NA is only one aspect of the MDG-based planning process, and is complemented by macro framework, macro and sectoral policies and institutional set ups, thereby addressing policy issues. NA helps identify policy gaps, and in that process, it is also a built-in process to refine existing policies. Lessons learnt indicate that this is a process which builds capacity. Costing tools are available for the following sectors: Education, Gender, Health, Water and Sanitation, Energy, Transportation, Agriculture, Environment, HIV/AIDS. These are comprehensive tools which require capacity building for government and other partners. Addressing all the MDGs without trade-off with the macro-economic framework is not always possible. Other lessons learnt are to prioritize and sequence interventions, develop a financing strategy, and integrate with M & E. In the plenary discussions, participants noted that while the needs assessment and budget planning exercises are bottom-up approaches, these have to be reconciled with budget ceilings imposed in a top-down approach, and wanted to know how these can be handled. It was explained that the first step is to do a bottom-up analysis to determine how much resources are required, followed by the next step to identify how much additional resources can be mobilized. Through prioritizing and scaling up of resources, it is possible to integrate needs assessment and budget planning.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "aba560a8-b013-4dbe-a13e-57895285a40f": {"__data__": {"id_": "aba560a8-b013-4dbe-a13e-57895285a40f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Develop