Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c6ca9105541e4086f93ba847d74204ced561dd3a58d9b4c15ac79cc4115961de"}, "3": {"node_id": "160560bb-24bf-48f5-91c7-d32b2855f19b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d939763061f90b2a0afc4c88c13a08ab066e43afce38b7a7c966f7c2172874ef"}}, "hash": "b6efe94fe584006b3469fa44ff45a05c2ff24cb7648ee449e8649da44388eded", "text": "terms of financing. Countries have to estimate the additional cost of addressing the required immunization coverage, particularly in hard to reach places, and work with the international community as achieving the MDGs is a shared responsibility. Introducing the HIV costing tool, Kazuyuki Uji, UNDP Regional Centre, Colombo The presentation made the distinction between AIDS (physical state in which the body\u2019s immune system is too weak to defend against a range of diseases or opportunistic infections) and HIV (the virus that causes AIDS). HIV is singled out from the other two diseases in MDG 6 because of its strong correlation with achievement of the other goals. With over 95% of HIV infections happening in 11. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries developing countries, HIV could greatly hamper poverty and hunger reduction efforts, with negative trickle down effects on education. HIV also disempowers women and young girls because they are more susceptible to HIV infection due to biological and cultural factors and unequal power relations between the sexes. Infants and children living with HIV tend to die early, and pregnant women with HIV are twice as likely to die as HIV-free pregnant women. People living with HIV are more prone to TB. In conclusion, HIV can negatively influence efforts to reach the MDGs. HIV has not yet taken a strong hold in the Pacific except for PNG, but according to ADB, the cost of the epidemic for the Pacific region is increasing. Factors fuelling HIV escalation in the Pacific include mobility; young population structure in Melanesia, particularly young girls and women; low contraceptive use, particularly condom use; strong stigma and discrimination against people living with HIV; and geographical difficulty in accessing services. Human rights based responses to HIV, Kazuyuki Uji, UNDP Regional Centre, Colombo The UNGASS Declaration reaffirms the full realisation of human rights (HR) as an essential element in the global response on HIV. To realise HR guaranteed by HR instruments, it is critical to enhance the capacity of duty bearers to meet their obligations and right holders to exercise their rights. In the context of HIV, it means viewing people as right holders and not just beneficiaries. Human rights are important in the context of HIV because violation of HR can be both a cause and consequence of HIV infection. Often those who are marginalised or whose rights are violated are more vulnerable to HIV, reflected in more women being infected than men in developing countries, as evidenced also in PNG. The follow-up group exercise on HIV and human rights was meant to encourage participants to think through some of the issues and challenges that need to be resolved and the various stakeholders who need to be involved in responding to HIV. Workshop participants in plenary session. 12. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries Questions Fiji Tuvalu Nauru Vanuatu Solomon Islands What population groups face rights violation and how? Sex workers: stigma no information, violence by law enforcers; street kids - voiceless, lack of programmes; youths: out of school, drop- outs or push-outs through the system; women: single parents in patriarchal society: unequal opportunities to assets; children: orphans, lack of residential care services, neglect; elderly and people with disabilities: neglect, lack of facilities/ supportive environment; PLWHV: stigma, discrimination, dif\ufb01 culty accessing services Seamen: It is company policy to stop seamen with HIV/AIDS from working. Women, Youth and children: biologically and physically vulnerable - Children - Youth - Old people - Women - Disabled Women & children: domestic violence; sexual/ physical/ mental abuse; gender inequalities. Sex worker: Discrimination, minimal life-skills PLWHV: Discrimination Who are most vulnerable to HIV? Does national planning, costing and budgeting address HIV vulnerability based on a rights- based approach? How will HIV priorities be set for implementing HIV- related planning, costing and budgeting? - Wives of seamen - Students studying abroad There is budget allocation for prevention (awareness programs). None for care, treatment and support - Girls and boys (youth) - Mobile Persons with Money (frequent \ufb02 yer types) Public Awareness Sex workers, street kids, youth aged 15- 24, women, babies, defense forces - Address the causal factors: unprotected sex, high STI rates, overseas workers, age group most vulnerable.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_se