ning a national level health system and the costs of public health activities. Main components of a functioning health system include scaling up system-wide health HR (including clinical and administrative staff), facilities and infrastructure, and improving the system\u2019s ability to plan, finance, and deliver high-quality health services by strengthening management capacity, improving M&E and quality assurance, enhancing community demand for and access to essential interventions, and building capacity for health research and development. The presentation was followed by a practical hands-on exercise on the Integrated Health Tool. The MDG-consistent HIV model is designed to calculate the total cost of HIV responses, but does not \u2022 Assess the impact of a response on the future course of the epidemic \u2022 Examine the cost-effectiveness of responses \u2022 Set priorities The key features of the model are that it is simple and user-friendly, integrates the cost of the \u201cEnabling Environment\u201d, is consistent with the MDG timeframe and target-based approach, and is compatible with UNAIDS targets for 2010 universal access for treatment. It calculates the cost of prevention, ARV treatment, care and support, health systems and cost summary. Participants found the health and HIV costing tools useful and comprehensive, and wanted to know what level of government officials would use them, and whether they were conducive to any country. It was pointed out that the costing tools are generic and countries can adapt them to their particular context. In addition, while use of the health costing tool would be led by the Ministry of Health, for example, several ministries would need to get involved including education, water and sanitation, statistical offices, etc. The level of persons involved would be middle-level government officials with influence on policy. Countries should ensure that data sources are accurate and reliable before inputting into the models. Participants requested that UNDP provides additional training on the various costing tools to familiarize them with these tools. UNDP highlighted that the workshop is not a one-off event but builds upon the regional MDG workshop held in Nadi in 2006. As such, the next step is to work with government and non-government counterparts in-country to address issues highlighted during the workshop discussions.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f8d46ead-ada4-402d-854c-731c0c5a763b": {"__data__": {"id_": "f8d46ead-ada4-402d-854c-731c0c5a763b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d5366a4115bafda22687ec5cb4bdbeaee83eb76af6e427e88bed8d5dd31b1ff8"}, "2": {"node_id": "7c4bda9a-c7da-4345-9097-42da4c36efca", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2e37f2672f448c8a5b3b76fb801d99d5cbdf9bfafbecd82