ation on the Education Costing Tool, David Abbott, UNDP Pacific Centre The education goal in the MDGs promotes universality, equal access, and quality education for boys and girls in both urban and rural areas. The education costing tool was developed by UNESCO and later refined by UNDP BDP / RCC. Some further refinements are necessary so that the tool can be used by Small Islands States. The tool can be used to cost all aspects of education policy at all levels of education. It is a comprehensive model which can be used for discrete modules of education and can be tailored to meet the needs of individual countries. Data needs for the model include: (i) population and population growth rates to provide levels of education enrolment; (ii) selecting a base year data so that the model starts at a particular point; (iii) universal primary education almost reached for most PICs; (iv) measures to reduce the level of drop-outs /push-outs and the cost of these measures; basic education ratios (pupil / teacher ratio); current class size and target class size. It is necessary to look at implications for additional classrooms, additional teachers, teacher supply and qualifications, subsidies to poor families as well. Data needs include unit costs (teacher salaries, support staff salaries, administrative support, cost of books, additional classrooms, additional teachers, maintenance costs). Additional data include GDP per capita (as a basis to calculate teachers\u2019 salaries), annual salary increases, and efficiency gains. Participants were very interested in the education costing tool, and made the linkages between this and previous presentations. They were keen to know how the costing tool Workshop participants familiarize themselve with the HIV Costing Tool. 17. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries could be useful in factoring in the number of drop-outs or push-outs. It was noted that, in recognition that many young people are better at skills levels, the model can cost improvements to technical and vocational training levels to provide certain basic skills to young people. This will enable them to take advantage of opportunities in different fields such as various labour migration schemes in the Pacific. Discussions also highlighted that the model looks at the mainstream education system, but can be adapted to look at the cost of provision for children with special needs by inputting the data. Although the model is a budgeting tool, it can assist ministries to upgrade the quality of education by looking at what is needed to strengthen the system and cost these inputs. Session 6 - Objective: To look at how the energy costing tool can support policy development, and draw linkages between development processes, climate change and disaster risk reduction for poverty reduction and MDG Achievement, chaired by Banuve Kaumaitotoya, Fiji Energy & Poverty linkages: policy implications for achievement of the MDGs, Patil Balachandra, Consultant Energy is both the driver of the MDGs and its absence is the cause of poverty, as economic activities cannot be performed without energy. Human welfare is thus linked to sustainable economic development. Access to information through media such as television, internet, etc. is defined by the ability to adopt and use modern technologies, which transform natural resources into goods and services useful for human life. What matters most for the poor is energy end- use services which should be accessible, affordable, adequate and of high quality. From the MDGs aspect, cooking, lighting, cooling are important to improve human development indicators, particularly if the economy is dependent on agriculture and needs energy for preservation or transformation of raw material. Information - when translated into knowledge - brings informed decision-making. The oil prices vulnerability index, which ranks countries according to their vulnerability to rising oil prices, indicates that Melanesian countries (Vanuatu, Solomon Islands, Fiji, Samoa) are highly vulnerable to oil prices. PNG is in the medium category because of its oil production. Hardship is experienced in the Pacific due to high vulnerability to energy shortages, as access to electricity is relatively low (<25%) in Melanesia, except for Fiji where it is around 50%. Possible strategies to increase access to energy is through PPP, donor support, or independent carriers, which may not always be applicable in SIDS. Plenary discussions emphasised the linkage between oil prices and the standard of living in countries. Vanuatu, for example, has high energy use and if the price of oil continues to rise, it is likely to have an impact on people\u2019s living standards. It was also pointed out that 18", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f44473e6-b58d-41b2-b109-2721191aecdc": {"__data__": {"id_": "f44473e6-b58d-41b2-b109-2721191aecdc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "afbae34623e2e190694c98398ecbc8f58080100a0bb15bb58aa162b844a59c58"}}, "hash": "afbae34623e2e190694c98398ecbc8f58080100a0bb15bb58aa162b844a59c58", "text": "variables are needed to calculate the vulnerability index and that Pacific countries that could not provide the data for all variables are not listed in the index. The Mauritius Strategy, Climate Change and Disaster Risk Reduction: Implications for MDG achievement, Philippe Boull\u00e9, Consultant Disasters can set back economic development by years if not decades, and have serious implications for MDG achievement. It is important to address disasters as a component of NSDS, and anticipate how they can affect sustainable development. The Mauritius Strategy recognises that SIDS are located in the most vulnerable 18. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries regions of the world in relation to the intensity and frequency of natural disasters, and that they face disproportionately high economic, social and environmental consequences when a disaster strikes. The MS also stresses that adaptation to the adverse impacts of climate change and sea level rise remains a major priority for SIDS. These main concerns were embodied in the Hyogo Framework of Action (UN World Conference on Disaster Reduction, January 2005) which is now the UN blueprint for Disaster Risk Reduction. Geological and hydro meteorological hazards (earthquake, hurricane) turn into natural disasters (impacts on people and property) depending on the vulnerability of communities to these hazards. There is need to learn to live with risk, and to define at various levels what is the acceptable level of risk for the community concerned. Recent statistics show that 70% of natural disasters for the past 25 years are of hydro meteorological nature. Although there has been a decrease in casualties, indicating that disaster risk reduction activities work, economic losses have increased tenfold between 1980 and 2005. Recently, (2007) the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) has confirmed future threats of great importance for SIDS, such as an increase in the frequency of heat waves, heavy precipitation, drought, tropical cyclones, extreme high sea level, and the major projected impact of these events. Steps to put in place mitigation measures have been slow. Application of the risk management chain to counter the impact of hazards include: \u2022 knowledge including risk mapping at two levels (both hazards and perception of the hazard), vulnerability maps. These evolve in time and need to be regularly updated \u2022 Prevention (campaigns in schools, land use, building codes) \u2022 Preparedness (one essential measure is the early warning system) \u2022 Response and relief (coordination, speed, professionalism) and \u2022 Recovery and reconstruction The world conference on disaster risk reduction proposed that SIDS adopt institutional approaches to DRR and associate all stakeholders including NGOs, and others; build national platforms for action; work with UN Country Teams, regional and bilateral partners for response logistics. Proposals for action in the Mauritius Strategy include insurance and early warning systems. Given the vulnerability of some PICs to rising sea level and climate change, there was much discussions on this issue. Participants highlighted the importance of indigenous and traditional knowledge in dealing with disaster risk reduction, and wanted to know which agency provides support when a disaster occurs. It was pointed out that several UN Agencies provide assistance in this area: WMO is a lead agency for hydro meteorological issues, together with UNESCO which provides support for early warning systems. In many countries, UNESCO has provided financial assistance to build schools that are cyclone-resistant so that these are used as refugee shelters in case of disaster and cyclone. The UNDP Pacific Centre indicated that one of its three practice areas includes conflict prevention and disaster risk reduction and there is capacity to support countries on this issue. Presentation on the Energy Costing Tool, Patil Balachandra, Consultant The energy costing tool was conceptualised and developed by the UNDP Bureau for Development Policy, and later modified by RCB for the Asia and Pacific region. The tool is used to support achievement of the MDGs by reflecting and costing the prioritised energy needs of countries but does not address national energy planning. Participants were given an opportunity to see how the tool works in practice. They indicated that the tool would need to be adjusted to the context of SIDS for them to be able to use it effectively. 19. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries Session 7 - Objective: Making the link between national development strategies, costing and expenditure frameworks: Bringing it all together, chaired by Semu Malona, Tuvalu How to plan for MDG-based National development Strategies: a macro- economic framework, Yuba Raj Khatiwada, UNDP Regional Centre, Colombo MDG needs assessment is the first stage of the MDG-based planning process. The second step", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9c4420d5-40f0-4191-8845-21e2b7e89a7d": {"__data__": {"id_": "9c4420d5-40f0-4191-8845-21e2b7e89a7d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "735b8a5a186f583780d847c5b160be2355ee196e6276efc4e150783024af954d"}, "3": {"node_id": "9fdcb327-d9e3-4745-9f19-6af034f4ccd4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4931b9500bf07596fdbe3eca3f7bf755c897868fe31524a97f63e7ab1234a999"}}, "hash": "20323eed670dd343ab9adb3bea3fbf96f4486c97517b7dbf0e468c062a6772ae", "text": "is to link the MDG NA with the macro-economic framework and the financing strategy, and translate these into MTEF and annual budgets. This makes the link from MDG-based plan to annual budgets through a credible MTEF in an integrated manner. A proper institutional set up in the country is critical as this should be a country-led process fully owned by Government who should have capacity to do this exercise with backstopping from UN Agencies. The steps for MDG-based planning include: (a) launch the process with institutional set up; (b) review existing plans and establish baselines; (c) undertake MDG NA and costing through 2015; (d) develop the macroeconomic framework, policies, and financing strategy; and (e) integrate the MDG NA into long and medium term plans and MTEF. Some challenges exist. While growth requires investment in MDGs, MDG costing also requires prior information on growth. MDG NA does not estimate non-MDG public spending and private investment. The macro model thus needs to estimate spending and investment separately. The Simplified Macro Framework (SMF) needs to be customized to country conditions to make it applicable. The SMF addresses the extent to which poverty reduction is possible with investments identified by the MDG NA and private sector investment estimated outside NA which may not always match with the MDG poverty reduction target. The main strengths of the SMF is that it is comprehensive at macro-level and data requirements are light. As it links to the MDG NA, it is useful in budget programming; and the user interface can be customized for any country. The main weakness is that the sector resolution is limited, the distribution module uses single HH (over 100 income percentiles), and the population dynamic is exogenous. During the plenary discussions, participants discussed the relationship between the MDGs and poverty reduction efforts, and how to integrate these into NSDS with links to the MTEF. Participants also discussed whether the SMF facilitates pro-poor policy. It was explained that macro-economic reforms have not always been pro-poor and have sometimes led to people being denied certain services. The MTEF and the NSDS are interlinked, and usually strategies will address commitments made at national and international level. Countries also wanted to know whether support was available to ministries on the tools and how this can be coordinated. UNDP Pacific Centre stressed that the tools were being demonstrated so that participants can gauge whether they can be useful to their respective countries. Mention was made that Solomon Islands and Vanuatu can receive targeted support to progress the MDGs in 2008, and the Centre will take account of the needs expressed by other countries in developing its Workplan for the next few years, in collaboration with other UN Agencies. 20. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries Session 7 - Objective: Linking national development strategies, costing and expenditure frameworks, chaired by Will Parks, UNICEF Budgeting to achieve the MDGs: Medium Term Expenditure Frameworks, Annual budgets and pro-poor budgets, Emmanuel Cuvillier, UNDP Mauritius The failure to link policy, planning and budgeting is the single most important cause of poor budgeting outcomes in developing countries. The Medium Term Expenditure Framework (MTEF) is now widely accepted in many countries as the most appropriate framework for strategic expenditure programming and budget restructuring. In many respects, MTEF has become the new panacea of public expenditure management for the inadequacies of planning and budgeting systems and broader performance problems at the sector level. It is rational to plan and manage finances in an integrated manner, with a medium term perspective. The MTEF approach is based on the recognition that resources are limited and unlikely to increase in the medium term. The MTEF does not result in a higher level of resources; instead it is a tool to determine available resources and allocate these in line with Government\u2019s priorities. The MTEF approach involves bringing together all resources available to ministries in a common basket to enable them to achieve a clear purpose. The MTEF process involves assessing total resources available to Government as a whole, estimating the actual costs of policies in each sector and then comparing these resources to requirements. These policies, and the activities required to implement them, will need to be revisited and activities scaled down to fit within available resources.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9fdcb327-d9e3-4745-9f19-6af034f4ccd4": {"__data__": {"id_": "9fdcb327-d9e3-4745-9f19-6af034f4ccd4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "735b8a5a186f583780d847c5b160be2355ee196e6276efc4e150783024af954d"}, "2": {"node_id": "9c4420d5-40f0-4191-8845-21e2b7e89a7d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "20323eed670dd343ab9adb3bea3fbf96f4486c97517b7dbf0e468c062a6772ae"}}, "hash": "4931b9500bf07596fdbe3eca3f7bf755c897868fe31524a97f63e7ab1234a999", "text": "The overall objective of the MTEF approach is rooted in the effort to address the weaknesses of the budgeting system such as arbitrary cuts in estimates; separate recurrent and investment budgets; and lack of transparency in the basis for budgetary allocations. These generally derive from the lack of a linkage between ministries policy", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0bdcb080-10fd-4c55-aaae-88516f5e066d": {"__data__": {"id_": "0bdcb080-10fd-4c55-aaae-88516f5e066d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "38e42d44d44b8329a2444a47505996e0bad25a70791e9c984ce85c33103bfc72"}}, "hash": "38e42d44d44b8329a2444a47505996e0bad25a70791e9c984ce85c33103bfc72", "text": "objectives and national priorities, and between ministries budgets and their policies, which usually far exceed the limited national resources. The MTEF is based on four goals: 1) Introduce a strategic basis to budget preparation so that expenditures are aimed at achieving agreed objectives; 2) Produce integrated, broad based budgets that integrate both recurrent and capital expenditures funded by Government and development partners; 3) Focus on the performance of ministries and measure the efficiency of total resource use; and 4) Introduce a three-year perspective so that ministries can plan ahead. The key elements of the MTEF is a clearly defined macro economic framework to determine availability of resources for key activities; setting priorities; information on efficiency savings; a policy process to reconcile revenues with how to spend the new savings; providing statistical data on public finance; determining baseline estimate of current policies and forward estimates. At any one time, three budgets will be at various stages of the budget cycle. The discussions on the MTEF highlighted the need for reliable data so that countries can monitor the impact of public expenditure based on key performance indicators. Proxy data can be used or new data developed by Ministries or Statistical Offices in the absence of comprehensive reliable data. Participants tried to integrate the different sessions, and wanted to know how costing relates to the MTEF. It was explained that while costing is a useful tool to know how much resources are required, the MTEF would determine 21. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries how much resources can be spent and why. The tools enable countries to determine the cost of strategies, while performance indicators show how the impact of expenditure will be monitored and measured. Participants pointed out that it is quite challenging to develop and work with social data. A recommendation was made for countries to learn from and share knowledge with each other through a South-South modality. Programme-Based Budgeting, Emmanuel Cuvillier, UNDP Mauritius Performance budgeting seeks to improve expenditure efficiency by systematically linking funding to results, making use of performance information to achieve that linkage. It aims to redesign the budget process so as to improve the allocations of public expenditure, so that it is directed towards services of greater social value, and also to boost both allocative and technical efficiency. Programme-Based Budgeting (PBB) places primary emphasis upon allocative efficiency and, more specifically, upon improving expenditure prioritization in the budget preparation process. Good expenditure prioritization is particularly essential when Government faces new and unexpected challenges which require substantial expenditure responses. Budgeting is therefore necessarily about expenditure choices and these choices are often tough. The tighter the aggregate expenditure constraints facing a Government, the more important it is to be able to prioritize expenditure well. Whether achieved through better expenditure prioritization, or through improved efficiency and effectiveness at the ministry level, the social benefits of increased expenditure efficiency are clear, and to some extent, seek to reduce the upward pressure on public expenditure over time. Good expenditure prioritization should also have the same effect of facilitating aggregate expenditure restraint over the medium and long term by helping to finance new priorities by cuts in low-priority existing programmes and sub-programmes. PBB can be implemented in 7 steps: highlight strategic priorities; define a structure of programme and sub-programme; identify measurable outcomes for each of the above; group activities relating to the same outcome or objective; define outputs for delivery of public services; identify key performance indicators to monitor delivery of outputs; undertake monitoring twice a year. PBB is a basic tool to ensure that ministries and parastatal bodies receiving budget allocations deliver value for money from public funds. Most governments look for greater accountability rather than more control. Assessing budget performance is therefore an important step, and can be derived from KPI that are measurable and verifiable. Session 8 - Objective: Linking national development strategies, costing and expenditure frameworks, including gender responsive budgets, chaired by David Smith, UNESCAP Gender-responsive budgeting: concepts, benefits and methodology for Pacific countries, Katrin Schneider, Consultant Gender responsive budgeting is an approach to mainstream a gender perspective into all stages of the policy, planning and budget processes. Gender is a social construct with roles and responsibilities of and attitudes to men and women determined by society. Women\u2019s and men\u2019s priorities often differ in society and the way governments spend money or raises revenues may have a disproportionately negative impact on women. There are five dimensions that should be considered when analysing gender equality in relation to budgets: public employment, users of publicly funded services 22. Sub Regional Workshop on", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1f34a394-bbfa-48b3-a38e-f603d9ab99c5": {"__data__": {"id_": "1f34a394-bbfa-48b3-a38e-f603d9ab99c5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based Planning, Costing and Budgeting for Western Pacific Countries", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "096cba8ca3009436b2f00c5583e4a983ad976a72cb14e7a9b22ac655b563c8c4"}, "3": {"node_id": "be504aab-8a1e-45ac-82a3-edf2626c4289", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/sub-regional-workshop-mdg-based-planning-costing-and-budgeting-western-pacific-countries", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2af2ffe68f2c0c796d5fc9907bf74c8859dc44fd95362405a943010c2ce19fdd"}}, "hash": "a91c357ea6d3c5e9fe9a36a721aea6238e85569cef5ad65ee3a90808c5b43fe1", "text": "MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries which is the main task of a government; transfers from governments to households; time use patterns; and decision-making. It is important to ensure that public spending is adequate to men\u2019s and women\u2019s needs, and to reallocate the budget to reduce disparities if it is not. GRB is not a separate budget for women, and its advantages include the possibility to monitor achievement of policy goals and to alleviate poverty more effectively. Gender equality is a fundamental human right, but can also help to increase economic efficiency, and thus, stimulate gender equitable economic growth. An important distinction from pro-poor budgeting is that GRB does not only look at the household level but also looks into the household, as resources, time burden and access to services are not always equally distributed among household members. In addition, it explicitly takes the so-called care economy into account which consists of reproductive activities that are not included in the System of National Accounts (SNA), e.g. caring for children or the elderly, cleaning, cooking or shopping. Different ways to incorporate unpaid work into the economy have been devised, with different valuation methods (input and output value methods) for unpaid work. PBB is a very good entry point for GRB because it can define objectives, targets, indicators and activities in a sex- disaggregated and gender-sensitive way. GRB is not necessarily about more money but better spending to achieve MDG3 and other additional indicators of gender equality. Measures to implement GRB include the sensitisation of government officials, the change of attitudes, training and capacity building, the change of budget formats, guidelines and manuals, the collection of sex-disaggregated and time use data, the analysis of current expenditure, and the undertaking of a Gender Needs Assessment. During the plenary discussions, participants highlighted efforts being made in their countries towards gender mainstreaming. The point was stressed that GRB affects both men and women, and that sex disaggregated data is a key to identify disparities and discrimination, as well as entry points for better policies. It was also emphasised that many stakeholders can play a key role in GRB, not only the Ministry of Finance. Those involved in women\u2019s development, CSOs, the media, parliamentarians, researchers, other Ministries, and the Ministry of Women all play a role in making the case for GRB and in its implementation. In many instances, the Ministry of Women needs capacity strengthening to better negotiate budget allocations with the Ministry of Finance. The role of strong leadership in implementing budget reforms including GRB was emphasized, and the need to train / sensitize leaders to understand the issues was raised. Examples of countries where Ministers have been trained in budget issues from a gender perspective were provided. The discussions were followed by a group exercise to encourage participants to work through some of the steps that need to be taken when implementing GRB, identify constraints they are likely to face and action points. Session 9 - Objective: Action planning and the way forward, chaired by David Abbott, UNDP Pacific Centre The objective of Session 9 was to identify countries\u2019 priorities over the next 2 years, and determine the support needed from UN Agencies. The discussions linked back to the various components of the workshop, and were grouped around 4 issues: (i) formulation of new/ review of existing NSDS; (ii) poverty & MDGs; (iii) policy formulation; and (iv) the costing tools. Country responses are provided in the matrix below 23. Sub Regional Workshop on MDG-based planning, costing and budgeting for Western Paci\ufb01 c countries Countries NSDS Poverty / MDGs Policy Costing tools Fiji Vanuatu Draft Sustainable Economic Empowerment Development Strategy (SEEDS) 2008-2010 developed and will be reviewed in 2009. Support needed to incorporate census data in SEEDS in 2009, and ongoing strengthening of processes required for national planning, reporting, monitoring programme in Fi